The entry-point into the pretty printer seems to be [this call in `driver::pretty::pretty_print_input`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/522d09dfecbeca1595f25ac58c6d0178bbd21d7d/src/librustc_driver/pretty.rs#L566-L573).
`call_with_pp_support` handles `--pretty=typed` [by running analysis passes itself](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/522d09dfecbeca1595f25ac58c6d0178bbd21d7d/src/librustc_driver/pretty.rs#L147-L154), which isn't exactly what we want.
By combining those two, we get 

``` rust
let src_name = source_name(input);
let src = sess.codemap().get_filemap(&src_name)
                        .src.as_bytes().to_vec();
// For this you'd have to make TypedAnnotation's analysis field public.
let annotation = TypedAnnotation { analysis: analysis };
pprust::print_crate(sess.codemap(),
                    sess.diagnostic(),
                    ast_map.krate(),
                    src_name.to_string(),
                    &mut MemReader::new(src),
                    box old_io::File::create(&pp_out).unwrap(),
                    &annotation
                    true).unwrap();
let analysis = annotation.analysis;
```

which can be inserted [at this point in compile_input](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/522d09dfecbeca1595f25ac58c6d0178bbd21d7d/src/librustc_driver/driver.rs#L122).

`pp_out_path` is still missing, but I think the following method should produce an unique path for each `rustc` invocation during the build:

``` rust
let pp_out = outputs.with_extension("rs");
let pp_out_file = pp_out.as_str().expect("non-utf8 pp output file").replace("/", "--");
// If this doesn't work, hardcode an absolute path here.
let pp_out_path = Path::new(concat!(env!(CFG_BUILD_DIR), "int-suffix-pp")).join(pp_out_file);
```

Aside from that, you would also need to hack the pretty-printer so it doesn't [output integer suffixes](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/blob/522d09dfecbeca1595f25ac58c6d0178bbd21d7d/src/libsyntax/print/pprust.rs#L2775-L2786) - should be easy to treat them just like the unsuffixed cases.

@cramertj Well, I gave up on trying to remove integer suffixes from the language, before 1.0 I was convinced we could replace them with type ascription.
And the tools I used to automatically check actual impact are beyond rebasing.

One can still clean up existing code by hand, of course.
